# Project Specification Rules (.cursorrules)

You must strictly follow all rules defined in this document.
Do not deviate unless explicitly instructed.

==================================================

1. # Project Overview

Project Goal:

- Build a sports prediction MVP platform using AI.

Target Users:

- Sports fans and bettors seeking data-driven insights.

Core Value:

- Objective prediction based on data, not intuition.

================================================== 2. Tech Stack (Strict)
==================================================

You MUST use the following stack only:

- Framework: Next.js 16 (App Router)
- Language: TypeScript (Strict mode enabled)
- Styling: Tailwind CSS + Shadcn UI
- State Management: Zustand

================================================== 3. TypeScript & General Rules
==================================================

- TypeScript strict mode must be enabled.
- The `any` type is strictly forbidden.
- All types must be explicitly defined.
- Prefer type inference only when it is 100% safe.

================================================== 4. Component Rules
==================================================

Component Definition:

- All components MUST be written as arrow functions.
- Use the following format ONLY:

  export const ComponentName = () => {}

Props:

- Props MUST be defined using `interface`.
- Props interfaces MUST use the `Props` suffix.
  Example: UserCardProps

Export:

- All components must be named exports.

================================================== 5. Styling Rules
==================================================

- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling.
- Class order must follow automatic sorting (Headwind).
- Conditional styling MUST use `cn()` utility (clsx + tailwind-merge).
- Inline styles are forbidden unless unavoidable.

================================================== 6. Naming Conventions
==================================================

File & Folder Naming:

- Component files: PascalCase
  Example: UserProfile.tsx

- Utility / config files: camelCase
  Example: authUtils.ts

- Next.js route folders: kebab-case
  Example: app/my-page/page.tsx

Variables & Functions:

- camelCase
  Example: fetchUserData

Constants:

- UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
  Example: MAX_RETRY_COUNT

Types & Interfaces:

- PascalCase
  Example: UserResponse

================================================== 7. Function Naming Rules (Verb-Based)
==================================================

Use consistent verb prefixes to make intent predictable.

Data Fetching:

- fetch... : API calls
  Example: fetchUserList

- get... : Derived or internal values
  Example: getUserFullName

User Actions:

- handle... : Internal event handlers
  Example: handleSubmit

- on... : Props event handlers
  Example: onClick

State Management:

- set... : Local state updates
  Example: setUser

- update... : Remote or DB updates
  Example: updateUserProfile

Validation:

- check... : Validation with side effects
  Example: checkPermission

- validate... : Returns boolean or throws error
  Example: validateEmail

================================================== 8. Boolean Naming Rules
==================================================

Boolean variables MUST use question-based prefixes:

- is... : State conditions
  Example: isLoading, isVisible

- has... : Ownership or inclusion
  Example: hasPermission

- should... : Conditional execution or rendering
  Example: shouldRenderSidebar

Forbidden:

- loading, open, valid (noun/adjective-only names)

================================================== 9. Type & Interface Suffix Rules
==================================================

Use suffixes to clarify responsibility:

- ...Props : Component props
- ...Response : API responses
- ...Params : Function parameter objects

================================================== 10. Error Handling
==================================================

- All API errors MUST be handled.
- Errors MUST be shown to users using a Toast notification.
- Silent failures are forbidden.

================================================== 11. Comments & Documentation
==================================================

- Complex logic (10+ lines) MUST include Korean comments.
- Use JSDoc for functions with non-obvious behavior.
- Comments should explain "why", not "what".

================================================== 12. Component Size Rules
==================================================

Maximum lines per component: 250 lines

Small Components (50–100 lines):

- Buttons
- Inputs
- Cards
- Single-responsibility UI elements

Medium Components (100–250 lines):

- Forms
- Modals
- Navigation bars
- Components with multiple child elements but limited complexity

Large components beyond this size are NOT allowed.

==================================================
END OF RULES
